      <hedline>
        <hl1>On the Grand Day for Bush, American Voices</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Tom Feeley letter welcomes Colin L Powell's challenge to two fundamental tenets of Republican dogma: war on drugs and expansion of country's prison system (Aug 1 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Republicans Open Convention, Emphasizing Unity'' (front page, Aug. 1): Colin L. Powell directly challenged two fundamental tenets of Republican dogma. His criticisms of both the war on drugs and the expansion of the country's prison system reopen a long-closed debate on a central issue in American politics: how do we as Americans best confront the related issues of race, class, education and crime?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Republicans Open Convention, Emphasizing Unity'' (front page, Aug. 1): Colin L. Powell directly challenged two fundamental tenets of Republican dogma. His criticisms of both the war on drugs and the expansion of the country's prison system reopen a long-closed debate on a central issue in American politics: how do we as Americans best confront the related issues of race, class, education and crime?</p>
        <p>I applaud General Powell for his audacity and integrity in challenging two politically popular Republican issues. I would like to know what the candidates think about this issue before I cast my vote in November.</p>
        <p>TOM FEELEY  Portland, Ore., Aug. 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
